   prematurely, causing a memory error.
   
   To fix this issue, I would recommend changing the way the
   `Exiv2::Image::AutoPtr` object is being used. Instead of using an `AutoPtr`,
   I would use a regular pointer and manually manage the memory. Here's a
   minimal local fix:
   
   ```
   //...
   int main(int argc, char** argv) {
       Exiv2::Image* image = Exiv2::ImageFactory::open(argv[1]);
       //...
       delete image;
       return 0;
   }
   //...
   ```
   
   However, this fix only addresses the symptoms and does not fix the root cause
   of the issue. The root cause of the issue is that the `Exiv2::Image::AutoPtr`
   class is not being used correctly.
   
   A more thorough root-cause fix would involve changing the way the
   `Exiv2::Image` object is being used. Instead of using an `AutoPtr`, I would
   use a `std::unique_ptr` or a `std::shared_ptr` to manage the memory
   correctly. Here's a more thorough root-cause fix:
   
   ```
   //...
   int main(int argc, char** argv) {
       std::unique_ptr<Exiv2::Image> image = Exiv2::ImageFactory::open(argv[1]);
       //...
       return 0;
   }
   //...
   ```
   
   By using a `std::unique_ptr` or a `std::shared_ptr`, we can ensure that the
   `Exiv2::Image` object is deleted correctly and avoid any memory-related
   issues.
   
